  "response": "The first touchscreen phone is generally credited to IBM and was called the IBM Simon Personal Communicator. It was introduced in 1992. The device was developed by a team at IBM and manufactured by Mitsubishi Electric. The Simon featured a touchscreen interface that allowed users to make phone calls, send emails, and use applications. It is recognized as one of the earliest examples of a smartphone, incorporating a touchscreen as its primary input method.",
